{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 21:46:29.627172", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — SDN spine–leaf lab\n\nScope and goal\n- Assess current network health, detect anomalies, localize faulty devices and identify likely root cause(s) using the collected host/switch state and ping tests.\n- No mitigation steps are proposed — this report contains findings, localization and root-cause hypotheses only.\n\nExecutive summary\n- The data-plane L2 forwarding is not functioning: hosts attached to the same leaf switch cannot reach each other and hosts cannot reach other hosts or the management/controller network from the data plane.\n- The OVS bridge objects for the switches (the logical bridges named for each switch) are in a DOWN state while their physical interfaces are UP. This strongly indicates the Open vSwitch dataplane (bridge-level switching) is not operational on the switches (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1).\n- Impact: Host-to-host connectivity on 10.0.0.0/24 is failing (hosts are isolated), and data-plane connectivity to the management/controller network from hosts is not available.\n\nKey evidence and observations\n1) Host interface and routing (host_1_1, host_1_2, host_2_1, host_2_2)\n- host_1_1: eth0 configured 10.0.0.1/24; route 10.0.0.0/24 -> eth0 (kernel route present).\n- host_1_2: eth0 configured 10.0.0.2/24.\n- host_2_1: eth0 configured 10.0.0.9/24 (RX/TX counters show prior traffic).\n- host_2_2: eth0 configured 10.0.0.10/24.\n=> Hosts have correct IP addresses and /24 routes.\n\n2) Ping tests from host_1_1\n- ping host_1_2 (10.0.0.2): result = \"From 10.0.0.1 icmp_seq=N Destination Host Unreachable\" for each packet; 100% loss.\n  - Interpretation: host kernel asserted destination unreachable instead of receiving reply — ARP/neighbor resolution or L2 forwarding failed.\n- ping host_2_1 (10.0.0.9): timed out (command exceeded timeout / network unreachable / no responses).\n- ping 20.0.0.100 (controller mgmt net): \"connect: Network is unreachable\".\n  - Interpretation: host_1_1 cannot reach other hosts or the management network via the data plane.\n\n3) Switch (OVS) interfaces and bridge states\n- leaf_1:\n  - Physical ports (eth0..eth12) are UP/LOWER_UP and are shown as master ofs (enslaved to ovs-system).\n  - But the logical bridge \"leaf_1\" entry is shown with \"state DOWN\" (bridge device down) and ovs-system appears state DOWN for the bridge-level device.\n  - eth12 has management IP 20.0.0.5/24 and is present.\n  - Notable counters: several physical ports show RX packets but TX counters are zero on those ports (indicating traffic arriving but not being forwarded at bridge level).\n- leaf_2:\n  - Same pattern: physical ports UP but logical bridge \"leaf_2\" state DOWN; management IP 20.0.0.6/24 present.\n- spine_1:\n  - Logical bridge \"spine_1\" state DOWN while physical ethX are UP and eth8 has management IP 20.0.0.1/24 with large counters.\n- Common pattern: the bridge device names (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1) are in a DOWN state while the underlying interfaces are physically up and assigned to ovs-system.\n\nLocalization — where the problem is\n- Primary impacted devices:\n  - leaf_1: hosts host_1_1 and host_1_2 are directly attached to leaf_1 and experience immediate L2 isolation.\n  - leaf_2 and spine_1 also show the same bridge-down behavior and are therefore likely contributing to wider connectivity loss.\n- The problem is localized to the switch dataplane/OVS layer across the leaf and spine switches (bridge objects are down), rather than to host IP configuration or physical link state.\n\nRoot-cause hypothesis (most likely)\n- The Open vSwitch bridge/dataplane layer on the switches is not operational:\n  - Either the OVS bridge instances (ovs-vsctl bridge objects) were not created/are administratively down or the OVS daemons (ovs-vswitchd/ovsdb-server) are not running or in a failed state.\n  - Evidence: physical interfaces exist and are UP, management IPs are present on separate interfaces, but the logical OVS bridges (named as the switches) are DOWN and traffic is not being forwarded (RX seen on physical ports but no TX).\n- Alternative/related possibilities (less likely but consistent with symptoms):\n  - OVS configuration corruption that left the bridges down while interfaces still bound to ovs-system.\n  - Bridge-level administrative shutdown (bridges created but brought down).\n  - Misconfiguration in the control channel that caused OVS to place bridges down (but the presence of management addresses indicates the node-level network is up).\n- Notably, this is not a simple host mis-configuration: hosts have correct IPs and routes; their inability to reach each other is caused by non-functional switch bridging.\n\nImpact and scope\n- Hosts attached to leaf_1 are isolated from each other and from other hosts in the 10.0.0.0/24 data plane.\n- Because leaf_2 and spine_1 show the same bridge-down symptom, the entire data-plane fabric is likely affected — cross-leaf and spine connectivity will be disrupted.\n- Management network interfaces on the switches appear configured and up (20.0.0.x addresses are present), so control/management plane may be partially reachable between switches, but the logical OVS bridging that performs L2 switching for hosts is not forwarding.\n\nConfidence level\n- High confidence that the immediate root cause is OVS bridge/dataplane not operating (bridge objects in DOWN state) based on:\n  - explicit \"bridge state DOWN\" entries for leaf_1/leaf_2/spine_1,\n  - physical interfaces are UP but logical bridges are DOWN,\n  - host pings showing ARP/neighbor failures (Destination Host Unreachable) despite correct host IPs and kernel routes.\n\nSuggested next diagnostic checks (for information only — not remediation)\n- Check ovs-vsctl show and ovsdb/ovs-vswitchd status on the affected switch nodes to confirm bridge existence and daemon health.\n- Inspect the systemctl status for Open vSwitch services on leaf_1/leaf_2/spine_1.\n- Collect ovs logs (ovs-vswitchd/ovsdb-server) for errors during startup or bridge creation.\n- Verify controller connectivity from switches (management IPs) and inspect OpenFlow connection status on each switch.\n\nConcluding statement\n- The lab’s data-plane forwarding is broken due to OVS bridge-level failure across the switch nodes (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1). Hosts are correctly configured but are isolated because the switches’ logical bridges are DOWN. The most likely root cause is that the Open vSwitch bridge/dataplane is not running or the bridges are administratively down on those switches.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 24413, "output_tokens": 3010, "total_tokens": 27423, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 13056}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1472}}}
